<div class="gpp-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-7">
        <h2></h2>
        
            <div class="gen-group">
              
                <div class="gen-group__logo"><img src="https://d1o1wdbk5ytaqh.cloudfront.net/media/Whalley_Community_Logo_-_2.jpeg" /></div>
              
              <div class="gen-group__content">
                <p class="subheading">Site managed by</p>
                <h2>Whalley Community Hydro</h2>
              </div>
            </div>
        
        <div class="gen-content">
          <p>A 600 year old weir, first built by monks in the 14th century on the River Calder in Whalley, Lancashire, has been harnessed to provide renewable electricity in the 21st century. </p>
<p>A variable speed Archimedean Screw was installed on the south side of the river in 2014, four years after a group of local residents came together with the idea for the scheme. The volunteer group grew out of Transition Town Clitheroe, a community organisation addressing peak oil and climate change.</p>
<p>Investors, mostly local, have invested varying amounts into the scheme, from £250 up to £20,000. Revenue generated through exported electricity will pay a dividend to investors, and surplus profits will be invested in further renewables and/or reducing carbon emissions in other ways.</p>
<p>The site is managed by Whalley Community Hydro Limited, a Community Benefit Society. Its directors are all residents of Whalley and the surrounding area.</p>
<p>Whalley Community Hydro was named UK Community Energy Start-Up of the Year 2014 at the UK Community Energy Awards.</p>
          <p class="read-more"><a href="#" class="button">Read More</a></p>
        </div>
        

